{{Multiple issues| {{BLP primary sources|date=November 2017}} {{BLP sources|date=April 2015}} }}
'''Loreta Anilionytė''' (born in [[Kaunas]]) is a Lithuanian philosopher, writer and translator.<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=http://leu.lt/en/structure/faculties-and-institutes/faculty-of-education/department-of-ethics-didactics/loreta_anilionyte-lozuraitiene|title=Dr. Loreta Anilionytė-Lozuraitienė|publisher=Lithuanian University of Educational Sciences|accessdate=30 April 2015|via=[http://www.bing.com/translator/ Bing Translator]}}</ref> She is an associate Professor of Ethics and Philosophy of the [[Lithuanian University of Educology]] and A Ph.D. of Lithuanian Culture Research Institute (formerly of Philosophy, Sociology and Law Institute).<ref name=Bio/> She graduated from [[Vilnius University]], Lithuanian language and literature.<ref name=Bio/> In 1991 she received her Ph.D. in history of German philosophy and ethics ("The Problem of Values in [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]] and [[Scheler]] ethics"). In her bibliography there are many published works including scientific articles and books, a novel and essay.<ref name=Bio/>
Anilionytė is the author of a highly controversial novel about the relationship between [[high culture]] and [[popular culture]] ''O kas po to?'' (''And what then?''). The novel is characterized by a mix of eroticism, philosophical ponderings on the human condition and psychological insight, social criticism and cold descriptions of moral failures. The prototype of this novel is a famous Lithuanian pop singer, [[Edmundas Kučinskas]]. Anilionytė is outstanding among other Lithuanian writers for her ironic, provocative writing style. She has been awarded some important literature prizes. She received the 2006 ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' magazine "Discovery of the Year" award for the novel.<ref name=Bio/>
She has translated many works by well-known German philosophers into Lithuanian. She was awarded the [[Franz Dovydaitis Prize]] in 2005.<ref name=Bio/>
