'''Metaphysical terms in René Guénon's works''' contains the definition of some [[Metaphysics|metaphysical]] terms used in [[René Guénon]]'s writings.

In his metaphysical writings, René Guénon has stated precise definitions concerning key terms in [[metaphysics]]. This article summarizes some of them. Guénon's writings make use of words and terms, of fundamental signification, which receive a precise definition throughout his books. These terms and words, although receiving a usual meaning and being used in many branches of human sciences, have, according to René Guénon, lost substantially their original signification (e.g. words such as "metaphysics", "initiation", "mysticism", "personality", "form", "matter").<ref>c.f. for instance ''The Eastern Metaphysics'' and ''[[Introduction to the Study of the Hindu doctrines]]'' w.r.t. the meaning of the word "metaphysics", the first chapter of ''The Reign of Quantity and the Signs of the Times'' on the meanings of the words "form" and "matter", the chapter "Kundalini-Yoga" in his ''Studies on Hinduism'' about the translation of Sanskrit word  ''samâdhi'' as "ecstasy", ''Man and his Becoming according to Vedânta" on the word "personality", ''Theosophism: History of a Pseudo-Religion" on the word "theosophy" etc.</ref> This article provides the definition given by René Guénon to some of the words used extensively in his works.

